// The two ensures clauses pin `post1_self_.seq@` and `post2_self_.seq@` to
// the *same* RHS `pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out)`. The previous
// attempt only asserted an implication, which didn't actually push the
// concrete fact into the SMT context. Materialise each ensure as a
// direct equality, then bridge them.

// Step 1: re-state each ensures-fact as a concrete Seq equality (this
// fires `=~=` extensionality so we get `==` on the seqs themselves).
assert(post1_self_.seq@ =~= pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out));
assert(post2_self_.seq@ =~= pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out));
assert(post1_self_.seq@ == pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out));
assert(post2_self_.seq@ == pre_self_.seq@.update(i as int, out));

// Step 2: chain through the shared RHS to get the two `seq@` values equal.
assert(post1_self_.seq@ == post2_self_.seq@);

// Step 3: `Ghost<X>` is determined by its view (`@`), so lift the Seq
// equality to equality of the `Ghost<Seq<A>>` field itself.
assert(post1_self_.seq@ =~= post2_self_.seq@);
assert(post1_self_.seq === post2_self_.seq);

// Step 4: `r1`, `r2` are unit, trivially equal.
assert(r1 == r2);

// Step 5: package the two field equalities so z3 sees that the
// `Array { seq, ar }` projections relevant to `det_set_equal` are both
// covered by the ensures-witnessed `seq` field.
assert(post1_self_.seq == post2_self_.seq);
